WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.160
Thanks everyone for joining. First of all, thanks to the organizers for putting

2
00:00:03.180 --> 00:00:06.400
together a session on metabolism and metastasis.

3
00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:09.460
And I know the concomitant talks on one

4
00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:14.330
memorial on Michael Bishop and another one on KRAS inhibitors that

5
00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:18.360
are happening just at this time, so I really appreciate that you decided

6
00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:19.440
to come here instead.

7
00:00:20.800 --> 00:00:22.140
So we will get going.

8
00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:33.840
I will just do a very brief introduction of today's session, and

9
00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:36.640
there will be three speakers, myself, and we have Dr.

10
00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:40.700
Pankaj Singh talking about nucleotide metabolism in the

11
00:00:40.760 --> 00:00:42.400
context of cancer and metastasis.

12
00:00:42.940 --> 00:00:46.600
And finally, Ralph DeBerardinis, who's going to tell us about

13
00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:50.320
NAD+ T5 and new roles for this hydrolase actually, which is

14
00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:51.740
beyond its canonical

15
00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:55.080
roles. I'm really looking forward to hearing from him.

16
00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:56.220
So why

17
00:00:57.040 --> 00:00:59.460
metastasis and why metabolism metastasis?

18
00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:01.520
If you ask me, I would say we've been

19
00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:05.700
studying wrong models of cancer for many, many years.

20
00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:10.400
Most of the mouse models that we've been using and most

21
00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:12.580
of the samples we've been collecting from patients

22
00:01:13.460 --> 00:01:15.680
through the years has been on primary tumors.

23
00:01:15.710 --> 00:01:18.880
And that's the biology we've been learning again and again

24
00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:21.830
throughout the last four or five decades.

25
00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:25.660
When actually how cells metastasize,

26
00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:29.200
it requires a completely different biology.

27
00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:33.060
First of all, for cells to leave their primary tumors,

28
00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:37.560
move through circulation, and get to the new niche, and being able to

29
00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:41.300
first establish in this new niche and grow, requires a

30
00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:44.320
completely different set of biological pathways.

31
00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:48.240
And for years we've been collecting biopsies on primary tumors from patients.

32
00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:52.340
You will not learn about that biology by studying those primary

33
00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:56.300
tumors. The same with cancer models in mice. Why?

34
00:01:56.340 --> 00:01:59.880
Because it's expensive. We don't want to wait long.

35
00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:04.380
Most of our animal models develop very aggressive primary tumors, and those are

36
00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:07.980
the ones we've been studying. So it took really

37
00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:12.160
a change in mindset for the fields to realize that we

38
00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:16.080
need both to start collecting samples from patients, metastatic

39
00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:17.800
sample from patients, and

40
00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:22.280
animal models that allow us to study metastatic disease.

41
00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:26.140
And although we've been learning through the years about these first three

42
00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:29.540
stages here, intravasation, latency, and then

43
00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:32.620
extravasation to establishing the new niche, how these

44
00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:36.500
micrometastasis establish in the new niche and how they start growing remain

45
00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:37.340
mostly unknown.

46
00:02:38.760 --> 00:02:42.680
Within the adaptations that happen in metastasis, how

47
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:46.580
metabolism changes in those cells remain even

48
00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:49.300
most unknown than in primary tumors.

49
00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:51.960
And that was the reason to organize this session.

50
00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:54.260
We believe the field is now ripe

51
00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:58.080
to be learning on unique

52
00:02:58.760 --> 00:03:02.630
metabolic adaptations in metastatic cells, and

53
00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:03.260
this is what

54
00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:05.760
this session today is about.

55
00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:08.120
So I will get started.

56
00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:18.340
And I will tell you about the work that my laboratory has been

57
00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:22.079
doing for the past, I would say, few years.

58
00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:25.440
I will give a very brief introduction on our work.

59
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.120
Some of you may know that I work on sirtuins for many years,

60
00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:33.490
but we've been studying metastatic adaptation for the past few years,

61
00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:35.680
and that's what I'm going to tell you today.

62
00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:39.420
And I wish I had time to tell you how I took that picture in the Grand Canyon.

63
00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:43.340
This was two years ago, and I got two prizes for this picture, so I

64
00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:45.940
am now not an amateur photographer anymore.

65
00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.240
So my laboratory has been studying this connection between metabolism

66
00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:56.240
and chromatin for many years. I call it an obvious link.

67
00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.040
This is two fields that for many people

68
00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:02.240
have been separated for too many years.

69
00:04:02.620 --> 00:04:06.480
People studying chromatin biology stuck to the nucleus and try

70
00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:10.120
to purify chromatin enzymes that were important to regulate

71
00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:10.620
chromatin

72
00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:14.980
pathways without looking outside of the nucleus, and vice versa.

73
00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:18.860
People studying metabolic adaptation, they mutually stuck to the mitochondria,

74
00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:22.900
sometimes into the cytoplasm. Definitely, they don't

75
00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:25.880
get into the nucleus when they think about metabolic adaptations.

76
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:29.800
But as exemplified here in a couple of

77
00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:34.200
diagrams, we cannot modify chromatin if we don't have

78
00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:35.520
metabolites to do it.

79
00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:40.120
Every single chemical chromatin

80
00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:42.480
modification requires metabolites.

81
00:04:42.520 --> 00:04:45.980
And here is example of S-Adenosyl methionine, SAM for

82
00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:49.940
methylation reactions. You cannot methylate DNA or histones if you

83
00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.440
don't have enough quantities of SAM, a major metabolite in

84
00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:57.400
many metabolic pathways. You cannot acetylate histones if you

85
00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:01.110
don't have acetyl-CoA, another major metabolite in many,

86
00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:03.200
many different metabolic pathways.

87
00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:06.940
And thirdly, you don't only need metabolites to directly

88
00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:10.720
modify chromatin, some of these metabolites are used as co-factor

89
00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:14.520
by chromatin enzymes. And one example is NAD, another

90
00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:18.440
major metabolite in multiple metabolic pathways that is used as a co-factor

91
00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:22.440
by many chromatin enzymes, among other sirtuins

92
00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:25.600
and PARP. And that's how my laboratory got

93
00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:29.200
introduced to that connection between metabolism and chromatin.

94
00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:33.820
This is a very brief summary of what the lab has been doing for many

95
00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:35.990
years. I won't have time to show you.

96
00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:40.170
I will need five days to go through all the projects that

97
00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:43.850
we are doing currently in the lab. But for many years, as I said, we work on this

98
00:05:43.850 --> 00:05:47.500
sirtuin called SIR6. It's an histone deacetylase, and we publish role for

99
00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:51.540
SIR6 as a modulator of glycolysis, of metabolism

100
00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:54.380
in cancer, particularly on primary tumors.

101
00:05:54.460 --> 00:05:57.860
We haven't studied its role in metastasis before.

102
00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:02.050
More recently, we became interested in other metabolic adaptations of cancer,

103
00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.400
and here are two examples. I will tell you today, I hope I

104
00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:08.700
have time, a few slides on a

105
00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:11.840
unique adaptation on one-carbon metabolism.

106
00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:16.280
And I won't have time to show you today on another project in the lab where we

107
00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:19.680
are studying how cells detoxify nuclear

108
00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:23.130
formaldehyde. And the same formaldehyde that all of you use as a

109
00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:26.840
cross-linker in your chemical reactions is produced endogenously

110
00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:30.840
by chromatin enzymes. And we still don't know how it is detoxified in the nucleus.

111
00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:33.700
I won't have time to tell you about today.

112
00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:37.880
My lab is still interested in chromatin roles in DNA repair, and we

113
00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:41.760
recently published a paper on a new factor that is important in a human

114
00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:44.090
syndrome, and you're welcome to go and look at the

115
00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:48.052
paper.But as I

116
00:06:48.112 --> 00:06:51.532
said, this is about metabolic adaptation in metastasis, and

117
00:06:52.152 --> 00:06:55.272
this is what we've been doing for the past few years.

118
00:06:55.632 --> 00:06:59.542
And the model we decided to study or start studying with

119
00:06:59.572 --> 00:07:02.752
is pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, PDAC. Why?

120
00:07:03.872 --> 00:07:07.552
Because first of all, it remains one of the most lethal cancers that we

121
00:07:07.632 --> 00:07:11.152
have, and at time of diagnosis, most of the patients will

122
00:07:11.232 --> 00:07:13.372
already have metastatic disease.

123
00:07:13.912 --> 00:07:17.872
And metastasis is what kills 90% to 95% of our

124
00:07:17.912 --> 00:07:19.672
patients when they come to the clinic.

125
00:07:20.272 --> 00:07:24.012
And as I said, we still know much less biologically

126
00:07:24.112 --> 00:07:26.412
about how metastasis develop.

127
00:07:28.672 --> 00:07:32.192
Very few cells manage to get away from the primary

128
00:07:32.272 --> 00:07:36.112
tumors to survive in circulation, and even less to

129
00:07:36.172 --> 00:07:37.472
establish in the new niche.

130
00:07:38.732 --> 00:07:42.652
And a couple of papers we were finishing a study on

131
00:07:42.692 --> 00:07:46.192
pancreatic cancer models with SIL6 in 2016.

132
00:07:47.272 --> 00:07:51.252
Thereafter, two papers came out in Nature Genetics, one from

133
00:07:51.312 --> 00:07:54.592
the work of Bert Vogelstein and Cristina Coccio, and the other from Andrew

134
00:07:54.672 --> 00:07:58.572
Feinberg, who is receiving this afternoon the Klaus Award that Ralph

135
00:07:58.872 --> 00:08:00.252
will be introducing him to.

136
00:08:01.112 --> 00:08:04.312
And in both of these papers, this was the first genomic comparison

137
00:08:04.892 --> 00:08:08.092
of primary tumors against metastatic disease

138
00:08:08.412 --> 00:08:12.192
pair-matched from patients. And the surprise for both of these

139
00:08:12.272 --> 00:08:16.192
studies were that when they look for genetic alterations, they didn't see

140
00:08:16.272 --> 00:08:18.852
extra genetic alteration in the metastatic cells.

141
00:08:19.392 --> 00:08:23.072
So for these metastatic cells to grow, they still maintain the same

142
00:08:24.092 --> 00:08:27.892
genetic drivers that the primary tumors carry, but they didn't acquire new

143
00:08:27.972 --> 00:08:31.452
genetic adaptations. And actually, Andrew Feinberg went one step further.

144
00:08:31.532 --> 00:08:35.413
He said, "Most of what I see are chromatin changes, and a lot of these are

145
00:08:35.432 --> 00:08:38.832
on genes that are metabolic genes." So this was descriptive.

146
00:08:38.882 --> 00:08:41.932
They just look at the genetics of sequencing of these patients.

147
00:08:42.332 --> 00:08:46.012
We have the right models to study what was changing in these

148
00:08:46.732 --> 00:08:50.232
pancreatic cancers in the metastatic

149
00:08:50.312 --> 00:08:53.392
tissues that were non-genetically happening.

150
00:08:53.932 --> 00:08:57.652
So, as I said, we developed a pancreatic cancer model, and we're to study

151
00:08:57.672 --> 00:09:01.592
SIL6 as a tumor suppressor. Eliminating SIL6 make those tumors much,

152
00:09:01.692 --> 00:09:05.592
much more aggressive, because it was driving a metabolic adaptation in the

153
00:09:05.632 --> 00:09:09.292
primary tumors. But an important point, and this was if you cross it to a

154
00:09:09.312 --> 00:09:13.272
K-RAS alone, which almost never get you tumors, but even in the

155
00:09:13.312 --> 00:09:17.032
context of K-RAS p53. In both cases, these animals

156
00:09:17.052 --> 00:09:19.092
develop extremely aggressive disease.

157
00:09:19.532 --> 00:09:23.312
And beyond what we saw in the primary tumors, what for us was striking,

158
00:09:23.752 --> 00:09:27.172
the animals developed, for almost 50% of them, liver and lung

159
00:09:27.212 --> 00:09:30.952
metastasis. And it remains one of the few pancreatic cancer models of

160
00:09:31.012 --> 00:09:33.292
lung metastasis today.

161
00:09:34.172 --> 00:09:38.132
Because we knew that these animals developed the mets so rapidly, we

162
00:09:38.152 --> 00:09:41.772
hypothesized this could be a very good model to study what is changing in these

163
00:09:41.792 --> 00:09:45.732
metastatic cells that it's not genetically driven.

164
00:09:46.072 --> 00:09:49.472
So we collected, when a postdoc joined my lab, Cristina Ferrer,

165
00:09:49.632 --> 00:09:53.572
I told her, "Let's work with PDAC." She came from a breast

166
00:09:53.652 --> 00:09:57.432
cancer model lab, and she said that we can do the same on breast cancer.

167
00:09:57.512 --> 00:10:01.492
When we inject primary tumors, in weeks, these animals develop

168
00:10:01.502 --> 00:10:04.972
lung metastasis. So we'll have a parallel model in a different

169
00:10:05.452 --> 00:10:09.112
tumor to study how these metastatic cells come up.

170
00:10:09.152 --> 00:10:13.112
So we collected RNA from every one of these tissues, primary, lymph node,

171
00:10:13.392 --> 00:10:14.172
and the mets.

172
00:10:15.032 --> 00:10:18.872
We got a beautiful Venn diagram, and many people has been doing this, and

173
00:10:18.892 --> 00:10:22.772
this Venn diagram gave us a lot of different interesting genes, some that were

174
00:10:22.912 --> 00:10:26.852
specific to liver, some that were lung specific from

175
00:10:26.912 --> 00:10:30.062
both type of tumors, and some that were

176
00:10:30.752 --> 00:10:33.592
same primary origin, different metastatic site.

177
00:10:33.972 --> 00:10:37.321
We decided to start with what we call the common metastatic signature,

178
00:10:37.892 --> 00:10:41.732
because we needed to start somewhere, and this was a collection of

179
00:10:41.772 --> 00:10:45.672
genes that were up and down in every single metastasis, independent of

180
00:10:45.692 --> 00:10:48.632
the tissue of origin, independent of the tissue of the met.

181
00:10:49.452 --> 00:10:51.692
Now, many people, as I said, have been doing this.

182
00:10:52.432 --> 00:10:56.272
We went one step further, and we decided to do a high-throughput sulforaphane

183
00:10:56.372 --> 00:11:00.072
assay to validate from all of these genes how many of those

184
00:11:00.152 --> 00:11:03.791
are exclusively going up in the mets and driving the

185
00:11:03.832 --> 00:11:05.421
growth of these metastatic cells.

186
00:11:05.772 --> 00:11:09.132
And we started with a sulforaphane assay because it has higher stringency.

187
00:11:09.482 --> 00:11:12.372
And when we did, it worked beautifully. This was a 96-well plate.

188
00:11:13.052 --> 00:11:15.032
For most of the genes, we saw no effect.

189
00:11:15.672 --> 00:11:19.272
For some of them, when we inactivated them by knockdown,

190
00:11:20.272 --> 00:11:21.732
the colonies disappear.

191
00:11:22.772 --> 00:11:25.452
So this was the list, was less than 10 genes.

192
00:11:25.892 --> 00:11:29.712
We further validated them by many different methods that I won't have time to

193
00:11:29.772 --> 00:11:33.692
tell you today. But from this list, we've been, and that's why the title

194
00:11:33.732 --> 00:11:37.392
of my talk is One Gene at a Time. We've been trying to understand how these

195
00:11:37.492 --> 00:11:40.492
unique genes are up or down in the metastasis.

196
00:11:40.572 --> 00:11:44.472
Specifically, what are they doing to allow these metastatic cells to

197
00:11:44.492 --> 00:11:47.612
grow? And this is the top genes here on the left,

198
00:11:48.432 --> 00:11:50.972
and I will tell you a story of few of these genes today.

199
00:11:51.052 --> 00:11:54.312
The first one is GSTT1. This is a glutathione

200
00:11:54.432 --> 00:11:58.112
transferase. When you think about glutathione, you immediately think about

201
00:11:58.172 --> 00:12:01.152
antioxidant adaptations. This is not the case for

202
00:12:01.252 --> 00:12:04.992
GSTT1. This is a transferase, so it conjugates

203
00:12:05.032 --> 00:12:08.712
glutathione to things. It's only almost exclusively

204
00:12:08.732 --> 00:12:12.012
expressed in the liver as a detoxifying enzyme. Okay?

205
00:12:12.072 --> 00:12:15.892
It conjugates glutathione to drugs, so we eliminate the drugs from

206
00:12:15.952 --> 00:12:19.392
our system. Endogenous substrate for glutathione in

207
00:12:19.452 --> 00:12:23.092
GSTT1 remains unknown, and roles for GSTT1 in

208
00:12:23.132 --> 00:12:27.092
cancer are also unknown. So we decided to study this,

209
00:12:27.172 --> 00:12:29.262
and we first confirmed the expression levels.

210
00:12:29.352 --> 00:12:32.032
You can see here in our own mouse model,

211
00:12:33.032 --> 00:12:36.552
and this is from the rapid autopsy program at MGH from human

212
00:12:36.692 --> 00:12:40.252
patients. GSTT in green, we see no expression in the

213
00:12:40.332 --> 00:12:44.132
primary tumors, massive upregulation in both the liver and the lung mets.

214
00:12:44.572 --> 00:12:48.492
So exclusively expressed in the mets, no expression in the primary tumors, and here

215
00:12:48.512 --> 00:12:52.416
it's validated by Western.2D growth, as I said,

216
00:12:52.496 --> 00:12:56.256
no effect on 2D if we eliminate. This is we see here CRISPR

217
00:12:56.636 --> 00:13:00.556
to eliminate GSTT1, we eliminate it with dox-inducible, no effect on

218
00:13:00.696 --> 00:13:04.016
2D. In 3D, the colonies completely disappear.

219
00:13:04.736 --> 00:13:08.716
And in vivo, the same phenotype. If we inject these cells into

220
00:13:08.756 --> 00:13:12.646
animals, the primary tumors grows unabated, and

221
00:13:12.776 --> 00:13:16.516
we expect that because there was no expression of GSTT1 to start with, so these

222
00:13:16.716 --> 00:13:20.116
primary tumors don't care, but the metastasis disappear.

223
00:13:20.476 --> 00:13:24.276
And here you can see in the lung, there is not even micro metastasis, a

224
00:13:24.416 --> 00:13:28.056
massive phenotype for this unique enzyme.

225
00:13:29.716 --> 00:13:32.656
It's not only required but also sufficient.

226
00:13:32.736 --> 00:13:36.676
If we overexpress GSTT1 on these cells and then we inject the cells into mice,

227
00:13:37.036 --> 00:13:40.676
we start getting ectopic metastasis in places where we never see

228
00:13:40.716 --> 00:13:44.336
metastasis. In here, including the skull mass, the shoulder mass, the ribs,

229
00:13:45.556 --> 00:13:47.495
and much more in the liver and the lung.

230
00:13:48.436 --> 00:13:52.236
So it's both required and sufficient as a driver of metastatic

231
00:13:52.296 --> 00:13:52.656
growth.

232
00:13:54.336 --> 00:13:58.316
How is GSTT1 working? Again, I won't go through a lot of data

233
00:13:58.356 --> 00:14:01.776
that took us to get here, but I will just show you the

234
00:14:01.796 --> 00:14:05.456
biochemistry. We use classic biochemistry to IP

235
00:14:05.556 --> 00:14:09.026
either GSTT1 interactors of glutathione-related proteins

236
00:14:09.416 --> 00:14:13.136
to try to identify things that are glutathione-related and

237
00:14:13.636 --> 00:14:17.326
interacting with GSTT1. And the mass spec, and

238
00:14:17.436 --> 00:14:20.996
many of the things that came down were extracellular matrix proteins.

239
00:14:21.716 --> 00:14:25.156
We focus on fibronectin 1, because it's a well-known

240
00:14:25.976 --> 00:14:28.616
major protein from the extracellular matrix.

241
00:14:29.096 --> 00:14:31.376
And we show that it interacts with GSTT1.

242
00:14:31.836 --> 00:14:32.956
And if you

