00:58:01.920 --> 00:58:05.820
more efficacy as a single agent. And I do believe, I think, particularly if

974
00:58:05.900 --> 00:58:09.760
we are trying to attempt to target primary tumor, I think it has to be with

975
00:58:09.880 --> 00:58:13.660
one of the maybe KRAS inhibitors, and then in combination with

976
00:58:13.720 --> 00:58:14.020
that.

977
00:58:14.960 --> 00:58:18.040
But it's going to be primarily in the metastatic setting.

978
00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:22.020
And I'm not really sure if different organ site metastases are

979
00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:26.320
also having different response to particularly this combination, but at

980
00:58:26.360 --> 00:58:30.200
least we do have some expression signatures that are showing

981
00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:32.400
induction, but some variations as well.

982
00:58:33.340 --> 00:58:33.540
Thanks.

983
00:58:33.600 --> 00:58:33.940
Thank you.

984
00:58:35.580 --> 00:58:37.620
Hi, Pankaj. Really great work.

985
00:58:40.020 --> 00:58:43.930
I was just wondering, in the MPA resistant cell lines, do they have any

986
00:58:43.980 --> 00:58:46.709
difference in growth rates and

987
00:58:47.720 --> 00:58:51.440
potentially protein synthesis rates as another mechanism

988
00:58:51.500 --> 00:58:54.010
of potentially conserving cysteine and

989
00:58:54.840 --> 00:58:55.940
allowing it to build up?

990
00:58:56.660 --> 00:59:00.280
That's actually a good point. They do actually grow a little slower.

991
00:59:01.020 --> 00:59:01.240
So,

992
00:59:02.260 --> 00:59:05.920
that could actually be happening in some capacity, I suppose.

993
00:59:05.960 --> 00:59:09.880
So there is some decrease in growth rate and hence likely some decreased

994
00:59:10.240 --> 00:59:13.820
protein synthesis as well that may allow them to also conserve

995
00:59:14.140 --> 00:59:17.020
some cysteine levels by themselves. That's a good point.

996
00:59:19.720 --> 00:59:22.120
Hi. That is very interesting and ardent work.

997
00:59:22.600 --> 00:59:26.460
And I noticed that in the initial screening, the dependency

998
00:59:26.560 --> 00:59:30.200
of the IMPDH2 is much higher than that of the

999
00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:33.720
PPAT and the PFAS. Both of the latter are believed to

1000
00:59:33.760 --> 00:59:37.680
be much more upstream and rate-limiting enzymes in de

1001
00:59:37.700 --> 00:59:40.430
novo purine synthesis. So, do you have

1002
00:59:41.380 --> 00:59:45.260
any thoughts or insights about the mechanism that determines

1003
00:59:45.320 --> 00:59:47.360
the dependency on different enzymes?

1004
00:59:49.500 --> 00:59:53.460
That's a good question. I think at some point, different enzymatic

1005
00:59:53.520 --> 00:59:55.700
pathways bifurcate. Of course,

1006
00:59:56.960 --> 01:00:00.920
cells do show decent amount of dependency on IMPDH2, but we

1007
01:00:00.960 --> 01:00:04.720
chose that primarily because there are existing FDA-approved agents against

1008
01:00:04.800 --> 01:00:05.020
it.

1009
01:00:05.860 --> 01:00:09.720
If we had the ability to develop agents, we could definitely look into some other

1010
01:00:10.460 --> 01:00:13.720
enzymes as well. But I do believe, I think, the

1011
01:00:14.520 --> 01:00:18.400
essential enzymatic nodes in any given pathway are going

1012
01:00:18.440 --> 01:00:22.080
to be somewhat preserved. And if it is

1013
01:00:22.100 --> 01:00:25.910
primarily because of nucleotide levels, I guess at

1014
01:00:25.940 --> 01:00:29.260
whatever level you're going to be able to inhibit, you're going to have efficacy.

1015
01:00:31.460 --> 01:00:33.860
It may vary in primary versus metastatic tumors.

1016
01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:38.600
There has been multiple other talks around how

1017
01:00:38.680 --> 01:00:42.420
salvage path-- There was actually a talk during the educational session by Matt

1018
01:00:42.460 --> 01:00:44.040
Vander Heiden, who was

1019
01:00:44.960 --> 01:00:48.660
talking about how there could be more dependence on the salvage pathway, among

1020
01:00:48.740 --> 01:00:52.240
other things. So, I think the dependence may

1021
01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:56.340
switch between the tumor site at any given

1022
01:00:56.420 --> 01:00:58.960
location versus metastatic versus primary.

1023
01:00:59.380 --> 01:01:03.120
But in essence, if you are inhibiting

1024
01:01:03.140 --> 01:01:06.620
enzymatic pathway and there's absolute dependence, you may have same efficacy

1025
01:01:06.740 --> 01:01:08.760
whether you have started upstream or downstream.

1026
01:01:09.100 --> 01:01:12.990
But there could be some ancillary reactions that actually are contributing to

1027
01:01:13.020 --> 01:01:16.160
the vulnerability, and that could be essentially different depending on what the

1028
01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:17.640
direction might be.

1029
01:01:17.760 --> 01:01:18.280
All right. Thank you.

1030
01:01:18.700 --> 01:01:18.940
Thank you.

1031
01:01:22.080 --> 01:01:24.840
Okay. We'll move to the last speaker of the session.

1032
01:01:27.120 --> 01:01:27.460
Here.

1033
01:01:30.430 --> 01:01:31.060
Raul Ramos.

1034
01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:37.500
Thanks a lot, Raul, for inviting me to come talk today, and it's great to see

1035
01:01:37.540 --> 01:01:38.680
everybody. Good afternoon.

1036
01:01:40.760 --> 01:01:42.700
Okay. These are my disclosures.

1037
01:01:43.900 --> 01:01:47.700
And, I'm not actually going to talk about metastasis that much, but

1038
01:01:48.540 --> 01:01:52.220
we got interested in nucleotide metabolism by studying metastasis, so let me

1039
01:01:52.320 --> 01:01:52.840
start there.

1040
01:01:53.820 --> 01:01:57.160
We're interested in metabolic pathways that promote metastasis.

1041
01:01:57.200 --> 01:02:01.162
And the way we study that in patientsIs to infuse people

1042
01:02:01.192 --> 01:02:05.172
intraoperatively with carbon-13 glucose or other isotope-labeled nutrients

1043
01:02:05.272 --> 01:02:08.552
while their tumors are being surgically resected.

1044
01:02:08.592 --> 01:02:12.552
And then we can use the labeling features and metabolites extracted from the

1045
01:02:12.592 --> 01:02:16.392
tumor to infer which metabolic pathways are active in the tumor

1046
01:02:16.492 --> 01:02:18.342
as the tumor is growing in the patient.

1047
01:02:18.452 --> 01:02:22.272
So we've done this hundreds of times in hundreds of patients at

1048
01:02:22.312 --> 01:02:23.812
this point using different tracers.

1049
01:02:24.372 --> 01:02:26.842
And the story that has emerged from that is that

1050
01:02:27.972 --> 01:02:31.971
tumors growing at the site of initiation are highly variable in terms of

1051
01:02:32.012 --> 01:02:35.972
their mitochondrial metabolism, and they can tolerate quite low levels

1052
01:02:36.012 --> 01:02:39.072
of mitochondrial metabolism in order to initiate and grow.

1053
01:02:40.372 --> 01:02:41.572
However,

1054
01:02:43.312 --> 01:02:43.732
tumors

1055
01:02:44.892 --> 01:02:48.652
that have metastasized or are going to metastasize tend to have a

1056
01:02:48.672 --> 01:02:52.172
shift towards higher mitochondrial metabolism, and

1057
01:02:52.272 --> 01:02:55.912
electron transport chain complex one seems to be particularly

1058
01:02:55.932 --> 01:02:57.072
important because

1059
01:02:58.072 --> 01:03:01.512
that complex is both necessary and sufficient to

1060
01:03:01.552 --> 01:03:04.871
induce metastasis in mouse models.

1061
01:03:05.092 --> 01:03:08.812
And that last part in particular was the work of Divya Baswata,

1062
01:03:09.292 --> 01:03:12.432
who was a great PhD student in the lab.

1063
01:03:13.052 --> 01:03:16.842
So variable levels of mitochondrial metabolism depending on the stage of the

1064
01:03:16.952 --> 01:03:20.232
tumor. And that got us interested in asking

1065
01:03:20.872 --> 01:03:24.712
which metabolic pathways are most sensitive to differences

1066
01:03:24.812 --> 01:03:28.772
in mitochondrial function. And so we've studied that in several ways,

1067
01:03:28.872 --> 01:03:32.732
but basically, the answer that arose for us

1068
01:03:33.292 --> 01:03:36.852
is that the way that cells maintain their pools of purine

1069
01:03:36.892 --> 01:03:40.652
nucleotides is incredibly sensitive to the level of mitochondrial

1070
01:03:40.752 --> 01:03:41.172
function.

1071
01:03:42.112 --> 01:03:42.312
So,

1072
01:03:43.492 --> 01:03:47.332
we've been talking about this a little bit for this session, but just to

1073
01:03:47.372 --> 01:03:47.932
remind you,

1074
01:03:48.832 --> 01:03:51.492
cells have two different ways they can make purine nucleotides.

1075
01:03:51.532 --> 01:03:55.232
They can build them from scratch, that's called the de novo purine

1076
01:03:55.252 --> 01:03:57.352
biosynthesis pathway, the de novo pathway.

1077
01:03:58.432 --> 01:04:02.332
Or they can salvage them, which means that the blue part here, that is

1078
01:04:02.372 --> 01:04:03.472
the purine base,

1079
01:04:04.812 --> 01:04:08.652
is effectively scavenged from the degradation of other purine

1080
01:04:08.712 --> 01:04:09.432
nucleotides.

1081
01:04:10.352 --> 01:04:11.552
And so,

1082
01:04:12.492 --> 01:04:15.952
what we and others have observed is that the level of

1083
01:04:15.972 --> 01:04:19.732
mitochondrial function basically dictates which pathway

1084
01:04:19.772 --> 01:04:23.752
cells use. Cells that have healthy mitochondria tend

1085
01:04:23.812 --> 01:04:27.192
to prefer the de novo pathway, whereas suppression of

1086
01:04:27.212 --> 01:04:28.322
mitochondrial function,

1087
01:04:29.392 --> 01:04:32.572
at least in part through redox effects, increases

1088
01:04:33.632 --> 01:04:37.272
the need for the salvage pathway. So mitochondria

1089
01:04:37.992 --> 01:04:38.692
dictate this

1090
01:04:39.932 --> 01:04:40.412
choice.

1091
01:04:41.532 --> 01:04:44.332
So,

1092
01:04:45.612 --> 01:04:49.362
let me just give a little bit more detail about these pathways.

1093
01:04:49.892 --> 01:04:53.552
And they're complicated, but they're going to be outlined in black

1094
01:04:54.412 --> 01:04:57.792
for the de novo pathway and red for the salvage pathway for the rest of the talk.

1095
01:04:57.872 --> 01:05:01.592
This is the de novo pathway. It's a long pathway, and it requires a

1096
01:05:01.632 --> 01:05:03.572
significant amount of energy and nutrients.

1097
01:05:03.632 --> 01:05:05.932
It starts with this enzyme right here called PPAT.

1098
01:05:05.972 --> 01:05:09.621
Somebody just mentioned this enzyme, which takes an activated pentose,

1099
01:05:09.792 --> 01:05:13.012
PRPP, and converts it into PRA, which is a

1100
01:05:13.072 --> 01:05:16.872
labile intermediate. And PRA then proceeds down the

1101
01:05:16.912 --> 01:05:20.792
pathway to inosine monophosphate, a purine nucleotide, and the other

1102
01:05:20.812 --> 01:05:24.312
purine nucleotides. That's the salvage pathway, energetically

1103
01:05:24.332 --> 01:05:28.172
demanding 10 steps here, and it requires the nutrients shown in the

1104
01:05:28.212 --> 01:05:28.752
boxes.

1105
01:05:30.352 --> 01:05:34.272
And in contrast, the salvage pathway is just one enzyme, HPRT1,

1106
01:05:34.312 --> 01:05:37.612
which takes that activated pentose, adds a purine base like

1107
01:05:37.632 --> 01:05:39.932
hypoxanthine, and you get right back to IMP.

1108
01:05:40.452 --> 01:05:44.102
So, a fast and cheap pathway versus a long and highly

1109
01:05:44.172 --> 01:05:48.142
regulated pathway. And so the question arises of how cells switch between

1110
01:05:48.172 --> 01:05:51.872
de novo synthesis and salvage. Biochemically, of course, we know

1111
01:05:51.932 --> 01:05:54.992
something about this. We know that the de novo pathway is under feedback

1112
01:05:55.012 --> 01:05:58.872
inhibition, at least in part at the level of PPAT, but the reality

1113
01:05:58.912 --> 01:06:02.612
is that it takes very high levels of nucleotides to achieve full

1114
01:06:02.672 --> 01:06:06.322
levels of inhibition. Seems like there might be other components

1115
01:06:06.352 --> 01:06:08.272
involved in this regulatory mechanism.

1116
01:06:08.732 --> 01:06:11.832
And so we went looking for those regulatory factors.

1117
01:06:12.472 --> 01:06:14.872
And one way you can do that is with a CRISPR screen

1118
01:06:15.832 --> 01:06:19.412
for genes that confer sensitivity or resistance

1119
01:06:19.992 --> 01:06:23.652
to thiopurine chemotherapeutics like 6-thioguanine or 6TG.

1120
01:06:23.712 --> 01:06:26.792
These were developed by Ellian and Hitchings back in the

1121
01:06:26.812 --> 01:06:27.732
1950s.

1122
01:06:28.632 --> 01:06:30.392
The

1123
01:06:31.312 --> 01:06:35.092
thiopurine bases are not toxic, but they get

1124
01:06:35.172 --> 01:06:38.942
scavenged by HPRT1 to make thiopurine nucleotides,

1125
01:06:39.652 --> 01:06:43.252
and those have two effects. They inhibit the de novo pathway, and they incorporate

1126
01:06:43.292 --> 01:06:45.892
into nucleic acids, and together those kill the cell.

1127
01:06:46.312 --> 01:06:47.732
So a screen for,

1128
01:06:48.572 --> 01:06:52.432
let's say, CRISPR guides that confer resistance

1129
01:06:52.472 --> 01:06:53.632
to 6-thioguanine

1130
01:06:54.452 --> 01:06:58.232
could identify genes involved in salvage or genes involved in

1131
01:06:58.292 --> 01:06:59.892
inhibition of the de novo pathway.

1132
01:06:59.902 --> 01:07:02.292
And these are the two things that we wanted to find.

1133
01:07:02.312 --> 01:07:05.832
And we were lucky because David Root's lab had done a screen just like this several

1134
01:07:05.852 --> 01:07:09.802
years ago, and they identified guides against two genes that

1135
01:07:09.872 --> 01:07:12.952
conferred resistance to thiopurines.

1136
01:07:13.192 --> 01:07:16.132
One was HPRT1, which of course is predicted.

1137
01:07:16.672 --> 01:07:20.392
And the other was a gene called N-U-D-T5

1138
01:07:20.852 --> 01:07:24.632
or NUDT5. And we validated both. Here are the wild

1139
01:07:24.732 --> 01:07:27.492
type cells that are sensitive to 6TG.

1140
01:07:27.932 --> 01:07:31.912
The HPRT1 deficient cells are completely resistant, and the NUDT5 deficient

1141
01:07:31.972 --> 01:07:33.452
cells are also quite resistant.

1142
01:07:34.712 --> 01:07:36.092
So what is NUDT5?

1143
01:07:37.072 --> 01:07:41.012
It's an enzyme. It belongs to the nudix hydrolase family, and it has a

1144
01:07:41.032 --> 01:07:44.962
known catalytic function to cleave ADP-ribose,

1145
01:07:44.992 --> 01:07:48.652
which is a byproduct of NAD metabolism, into

1146
01:07:48.752 --> 01:07:50.532
AMP and ribose 5-phosphate.

1147
01:07:51.532 --> 01:07:55.152
So Zheng Wu, the postdoc working on this project, thought this would be

1148
01:07:55.932 --> 01:07:59.872
easy to figure out because ribose 5-phosphate is the

1149
01:08:00.132 --> 01:08:03.532
precursor of PRPP, and that's the substrate of HPRT1.

1150
01:08:03.592 --> 01:08:07.412
So maybe what NUDT5 is doing is just providing the pentose for

1151
01:08:07.492 --> 01:08:09.092
the salvage pathway.

1152
01:08:10.432 --> 01:08:13.952
But that turned out to be wrong because reconstituting the NUDT5

1153
01:08:13.992 --> 01:08:17.516
deficient cellsWith wild type NUDT5

1154
01:08:17.677 --> 01:08:21.056
or an allele that is catalytically inactive, that's the

1155
01:08:21.137 --> 01:08:25.076
E112Q mutation, are equally good at restoring sensitivity to

1156
01:08:25.337 --> 01:08:29.257
60G. So that means that whatever NUDT5 is doing, it has nothing to do with

1157
01:08:29.297 --> 01:08:32.677
its catalytic function. And in fact, we also just tested the

1158
01:08:32.816 --> 01:08:36.337
HPRT1 reaction using isotope tracers, and it's completely

1159
01:08:36.356 --> 01:08:38.757
insensitive to presence or absence of NUDT5.

1160
01:08:38.816 --> 01:08:40.415
So something else is going on here.

1161
01:08:41.956 --> 01:08:45.736
So then we studied the de novo pathway, which is again shown

1162
01:08:45.816 --> 01:08:49.717
here in black, again with isotope tracing, but now using N15

1163
01:08:49.776 --> 01:08:52.616
labeled glutamine with a label in the gamma position.

1164
01:08:53.016 --> 01:08:56.976
That nitrogen gets incorporated twice into AMP that is

1165
01:08:57.016 --> 01:09:00.696
synthesized by the de novo pathway, and that's very easy to follow by mass

1166
01:09:00.717 --> 01:09:04.316
spectrometry. Okay. So the gray bars here show you that cells

1167
01:09:04.976 --> 01:09:08.837
with wild type NUDT5 avidly use the de

1168
01:09:08.896 --> 01:09:12.126
novo synthesis pathway and completely shut it

1169
01:09:12.236 --> 01:09:15.596
off when 60G is present. That was expected, but the

1170
01:09:15.637 --> 01:09:19.396
NUDT5 deficient cells can't do that, and they keep on using the de

1171
01:09:19.456 --> 01:09:21.516
novo pathway, even with the drug on board.

1172
01:09:21.576 --> 01:09:23.806
So there's a difference in sensitivity.

1173
01:09:23.876 --> 01:09:26.746
Okay, so in this system, what NUDT5 is doing is really

1174
01:09:26.816 --> 01:09:30.536
dictating whether cells can turn off the de novo

1175
01:09:30.656 --> 01:09:34.116
pathway when purines or thiopurines are present.

1176
01:09:35.516 --> 01:09:35.736
And

1177
01:09:37.036 --> 01:09:39.776
I think it's important that that's not just a fluke

1178
01:09:40.677 --> 01:09:44.456
of these thiopurine chemotherapeutic reagents because it also

1179
01:09:44.476 --> 01:09:48.196
occurs when you give natural purine bases like hypoxanthine.

1180
01:09:48.516 --> 01:09:50.396
This is an N15 labeling time course.

1181
01:09:50.436 --> 01:09:53.616
Here you can see the cells with wild type NUDT5 in gray

1182
01:09:54.177 --> 01:09:57.596
shutting off the de novo pathway when you add hypoxanthine.

1183
01:09:57.616 --> 01:10:01.506
But the cells lacking NUDT5, they keep on using

1184
01:10:01.536 --> 01:10:03.036
the de novo synthesis pathway.

1185
01:10:04.976 --> 01:10:05.276
And

1186
01:10:06.216 --> 01:10:09.296
that is why the cells are resistant

1187
01:10:10.756 --> 01:10:14.316
to 60G. A little bit of a side note, but I sort of always

1188
01:10:14.356 --> 01:10:18.316
assumed that the major mechanism of cancer cell

1189
01:10:18.376 --> 01:10:20.816
killing with these drugs was DNA damage.

1190
01:10:21.376 --> 01:10:25.316
Okay, that may be true in some systems, but at least in our hands, the

1191
01:10:25.356 --> 01:10:29.306
amount of DNA damage is no different in cells that do or don't have

1192
01:10:29.356 --> 01:10:32.786
NUDT5. Okay, what is different is whether they can use the de novo

1193
01:10:32.916 --> 01:10:36.736
pathway. And so we use these two drugs, lemotrexal and

1194
01:10:36.776 --> 01:10:40.076
methotrexate, both of which block the de novo pathway.

1195
01:10:40.836 --> 01:10:44.816
And as I said before, cells lacking NUDT5 are

1196
01:10:44.896 --> 01:10:48.836
fairly resistant to 60G. They're also fairly resistant to

1197
01:10:48.916 --> 01:10:52.096
inhibitors of the de novo pathway, but if you combine them together, now

1198
01:10:52.476 --> 01:10:56.046
60G becomes toxic. So what's keeping the cells alive is that

1199
01:10:56.096 --> 01:10:59.776
residual let's say, persistence of the de novo synthesis pathway.

1200
01:11:01.276 --> 01:11:05.196
Okay, anyway, mechanism. How is NUDT5 doing this if it doesn't require

1201
01:11:05.236 --> 01:11:09.136
the catalytic activity? It turns out NUDT5 physically

1202
01:11:09.176 --> 01:11:12.916
interacts with PPAT. That's the enzyme that initiates the de

1203
01:11:12.956 --> 01:11:13.836
novo pathway.

1204
01:11:14.636 --> 01:11:17.896
And we picked up this interaction

1205
01:11:18.036 --> 01:11:21.405
initially, computationally. Our

1206
01:11:21.536 --> 01:11:24.576
collaborator, Qian Song at UT Southwestern, uses

1207
01:11:24.616 --> 01:11:28.185
co-evolutionary signals to infer protein-protein interactions,

1208
01:11:28.896 --> 01:11:32.396
and she was the first one who alerted us to this possible interaction.

1209
01:11:32.876 --> 01:11:36.496
The AlphaFold model here predicts that residue

1210
01:11:36.676 --> 01:11:40.136
R70 on NUDT5 lies right in the interaction

1211
01:11:40.196 --> 01:11:40.756
interface.

1212
01:11:41.916 --> 01:11:45.846
So we generated cells with FLAG-tagged PPAT and

1213
01:11:45.876 --> 01:11:49.396
then showed that PPAT can pull down wild type NUDT5

1214
01:11:50.116 --> 01:11:53.716
or the catalytic mutant, but it can't pull down

1215
01:11:53.756 --> 01:11:57.316
NUDT5 that contains an arginine to alanine

1216
01:11:57.996 --> 01:12:01.916
mutation at residue 70. Okay, I should just

1217
01:12:02.076 --> 01:12:05.696
add that that mutation, the R70A mutation in

1218
01:12:05.736 --> 01:12:09.496
NUDT5, we don't think disrupts the structure of the protein

1219
01:12:09.536 --> 01:12:12.776
because it's still catalytically active, but it can't bind to PPAT anymore.

1220
01:12:13.436 --> 01:12:17.296
Okay, and that interaction is critical for this ability to shut off the de novo

1221
01:12:17.356 --> 01:12:21.256
synthesis pathway. Here are cells lacking NUDT5, okay, which keep

1222
01:12:21.336 --> 01:12:24.356
using de novo synthesis, okay, when you treat them with 60G.

1223
01:12:24.416 --> 01:12:28.396
I showed you that before. If you add back wild type or catalytically

1224
01:12:28.456 --> 01:12:32.436
inactive NUDT5, they shut it off. But if you add back the mutant that

1225
01:12:32.456 --> 01:12:35.976
doesn't bind PPAT, they keep using the de novo synthesis

1226
01:12:36.095 --> 01:12:36.595
pathway.

1227
01:12:37.655 --> 01:12:37.956
Okay.

1228
01:12:39.376 --> 01:12:42.776
I should say that in vitro, we validated this is a direct

1229
01:12:42.816 --> 01:12:46.376
interaction using recombinant PPAT and NUDT5.

1230
01:12:46.436 --> 01:12:49.976
Okay, so they bind directly. And then this is an in vitro

1231
01:12:50.416 --> 01:12:54.336
enzymatic assay using NUDT5, PPAT,

1232
01:12:54.896 --> 01:12:58.716
and then we added PRP and glutamine, the two substrates of the PPAT

1233
01:12:58.816 --> 01:13:02.716
reaction, just to use mass spec to monitor the production of glutamate.

1234
01:13:02.756 --> 01:13:06.496
And what you can see is that if you add in wild type NUDT5, it

1235
01:13:06.596 --> 01:13:10.286
inhibits quite potently, okay, about 80% of PPAT's

1236
01:13:10.316 --> 01:13:13.476
enzymatic activity, but the binding mutant has no effect.

1237
01:13:14.696 --> 01:13:14.936
Okay.

1238
01:13:16.636 --> 01:13:20.536
So what about in vivo? So we generated xenografts from those

1239
01:13:20.816 --> 01:13:24.776
same four cell lines, okay,

1240
01:13:24.916 --> 01:13:27.996
cell lines that contain no NUDT5,

1241
01:13:28.696 --> 01:13:32.336
wild type NUDT5, or either of the two mutants, waited for the

1242
01:13:32.356 --> 01:13:36.076
tumors to grow up, and then treated the mice either with a vehicle or with 60G.

1243
01:13:36.636 --> 01:13:40.556
Cells that don't have NUDT5 or have NUDT5 that can't

1244
01:13:40.636 --> 01:13:41.146
bind

1245
01:13:41.996 --> 01:13:45.796
to PPAT are completely insensitive to 60G,

1246
01:13:45.916 --> 01:13:46.336
whereas

1247
01:13:47.756 --> 01:13:51.556
as long as NUDT5 can bind to PPAT, the tumors are quite sensitive.

1248
01:13:51.596 --> 01:13:55.436
So this is a drug that's been around since the 1950s, and

1249
01:13:55.516 --> 01:13:56.596
NUDT5 is,

1250
01:13:57.476 --> 01:14:01.236
I think, a key component in determining whether the

1251
01:14:01.296 --> 01:14:02.356
drug can be effective.

1252
01:14:04.456 --> 01:14:07.216
All right, so I'm just going to summarize a little bit about the biochemical

1253
01:14:07.296 --> 01:14:09.296
mechanism. We're still working on this, but

1254
01:14:10.176 --> 01:14:14.096
the issue seems to be the oligomeric state of

1255
01:14:14.116 --> 01:14:18.056
PPAT. So it's been known since the 1970s

1256
01:14:18.656 --> 01:14:22.436
that PPAT is most active when it's a dimer.And less

1257
01:14:22.616 --> 01:14:25.776
active when it's a higher order oligomer,

1258
01:14:26.616 --> 01:14:29.556
such as a tetramer. And NUDT15

1259
01:14:29.976 --> 01:14:33.636
induces PPAT tetramerization. That's shown

1260
01:14:33.696 --> 01:14:34.396
here in

1261
01:14:36.176 --> 01:14:37.666
basically in a glutaraldehyde

1262
01:14:39.036 --> 01:14:42.736
assay. You can see increased tetramerization of PPAT in the

1263
01:14:42.756 --> 01:14:46.196
presence of wild type or catalytically inactive NUDT5.

1264
01:14:46.276 --> 01:14:48.986
But the mutant that doesn't bind PPAT, now PPAT

1265
01:14:49.916 --> 01:14:53.116
is mostly in the active dimeric state. Okay.

1266
01:14:53.956 --> 01:14:54.155
So,

1267
01:14:55.336 --> 01:14:59.296
I think what that means is that when NUDT5 can bind

1268
01:14:59.436 --> 01:15:02.696
PPAT, PPAT tetramerizes, and that

1269
01:15:02.776 --> 01:15:05.996
allows the abundance of purine

1270
01:15:06.016 --> 01:15:09.896
nucleotides to shut off the de novo pathway at the level,

1271
01:15:10.016 --> 01:15:13.196
at least in part, of PPAT enzymatic activity.

1272
01:15:13.816 --> 01:15:17.636
Okay? If NUDT5 doesn't bind, PPAT retains its dimeric active

1273
01:15:17.736 --> 01:15:20.396
form, and the de novo pathway keeps going.

1274
01:15:21.616 --> 01:15:21.796
So,

1275
01:15:23.056 --> 01:15:26.516
I would love to know what is the biochemical triggering

1276
01:15:26.556 --> 01:15:30.386
mechanism to induce tetramerization and

1277
01:15:30.416 --> 01:15:32.906
maybe even more proximally, why NUDT5 binds.

1278
01:15:32.996 --> 01:15:36.876
This is not constitutive, okay? And the fraction

1279
01:15:36.916 --> 01:15:40.636
of PPAT in the cell that is

1280
01:15:40.676 --> 01:15:44.476
bound to NUDT5 is extremely low, even in situations

1281
01:15:44.516 --> 01:15:48.376
where PPAT is inactive. So it seems like maybe a

1282
01:15:48.436 --> 01:15:52.116
kiss-and-run phenomenon, and we don't know what the biochemical trigger is.

1283
01:15:52.176 --> 01:15:56.136
We know that we can trigger the interaction by giving purine bases in

1284
01:15:56.176 --> 01:16:00.016
the presence of HPRT1. That suggests that it probably involves

1285
01:16:00.136 --> 01:16:03.896
these purine nucleotides or possibly a drop in PRPP or maybe

1286
01:16:03.976 --> 01:16:04.336
both.

1287
01:16:05.156 --> 01:16:09.136
Okay. But we need more biochemical insight into how this is happening, and I think

1288
01:16:09.156 --> 01:16:12.776
this is worth pursuing because this could provide a definitive mechanism of purine

1289
01:16:12.796 --> 01:16:16.576
homeostasis, which has been missing, I think, since this pathway was

1290
01:16:16.616 --> 01:16:17.996
worked out about 80 years ago.

1291
01:16:19.736 --> 01:16:22.936
Okay. And I just want to point out these other two great papers here,

1292
01:16:23.756 --> 01:16:26.956
that reported a role for NUDT5 in regulating de novo purine

1293
01:16:27.136 --> 01:16:27.816
biosynthesis

1294
01:16:28.636 --> 01:16:29.836
right around the same time we did.

1295
01:16:31.276 --> 01:16:33.866
Okay. Last thing to say is that,

1296
01:16:35.536 --> 01:16:39.276
it has to do with the way the purine biosynthesis pathway actually

1297
01:16:39.376 --> 01:16:43.336
operates in intact cells. Okay? I find this quite

1298
01:16:43.356 --> 01:16:47.296
interesting. So there are six enzymes, PPAT and

1299
01:16:47.416 --> 01:16:51.296
five other ones, that catalyze the 10 reactions between

1300
01:16:51.356 --> 01:16:55.216
PRPP and IMP. All right? And when

1301
01:16:55.256 --> 01:16:58.916
the pathway is active, they are co-localized in a

1302
01:16:58.976 --> 01:17:02.276
cytosolic super complex that Steven Benkovic named the

1303
01:17:02.316 --> 01:17:06.276
purinosome. And, the purinosome is thought

1304
01:17:06.336 --> 01:17:08.436
to exist to channel

1305
01:17:09.236 --> 01:17:13.056
phosphoribosylamine, that labile product of the PPAT reaction,

1306
01:17:14.176 --> 01:17:15.296
down to IMP.

1307
01:17:16.216 --> 01:17:16.496
Okay.

1308
01:17:17.556 --> 01:17:19.296
When purines are scarce,

1309
01:17:20.176 --> 01:17:23.236
you can see these purinosomes forming in cells.

1310
01:17:23.276 --> 01:17:27.125
They're these punctate dots here, and they show up because

1311
01:17:27.216 --> 01:17:30.676
one of the enzymes in the de novo synthesis pathway's been tagged with GFP.

1312
01:17:31.636 --> 01:17:35.556
And then if you add purines back, they just dissipate over the course of a

1313
01:17:35.596 --> 01:17:38.356
few minutes. Okay. So it's quite dynamic.

1314
01:17:38.996 --> 01:17:42.866
And we think part of what NUDT5 is doing is determining the

1315
01:17:42.996 --> 01:17:45.036
dissipation rate of these purinosomes.

1316
01:17:45.156 --> 01:17:48.716
I say that because cells that lack NUDT5 or that

1317
01:17:48.736 --> 01:17:51.056
express the PPAT binding mutants

1318
01:17:52.456 --> 01:17:53.876
inappropriately

1319
01:17:54.736 --> 01:17:58.636
allow purinosomes to persist. Here, the purinosomes are these black

1320
01:17:58.656 --> 01:18:02.625
dots, even when nucleotides are present, and that's quantified

1321
01:18:02.736 --> 01:18:05.876
here, and you can see the high level of purinosomes

1322
01:18:07.096 --> 01:18:10.796
in the R70A mutant expressing

1323
01:18:11.076 --> 01:18:13.316
cells. Okay. So,

1324
01:18:14.196 --> 01:18:17.236
two mechanisms by which NUDT5

1325
01:18:17.276 --> 01:18:21.056
regulates purine metabolism. One is the direct mechanism on PPAT's

1326
01:18:21.076 --> 01:18:24.676
biochemical activity, and the other is in the ability to

1327
01:18:25.056 --> 01:18:28.816
allow the purinosome to dissipate when

1328
01:18:28.856 --> 01:18:32.096
purines are abundant. And I have to say, I don't know which one is the dominant

1329
01:18:32.156 --> 01:18:35.916
mechanism. What we're trying to do now is to identify PPAT mutants that

1330
01:18:35.956 --> 01:18:39.656
retain their catalytic activity, retain NUDT5 binding,

1331
01:18:40.056 --> 01:18:43.435
okay, but cannot associate with the purinosome, and that would allow us to

1332
01:18:43.456 --> 01:18:46.916
know whether effective purinosome assembly is actually

1333
01:18:46.956 --> 01:18:49.376
required for efficient de novo purine

1334
01:18:49.396 --> 01:18:52.876
synthesis. Okay. Does this matter in people?

1335
01:18:53.676 --> 01:18:57.656
It does seem to matter in people. This is a beautiful study from Jun Yang

1336
01:18:57.856 --> 01:18:58.016
at

1337
01:18:58.996 --> 01:19:01.736
St. Jude's, and what he did was to genotype

1338
01:19:03.756 --> 01:19:04.396
patients.

1339
01:19:05.856 --> 01:19:09.476
These were pediatric patients with acute

1340
01:19:09.516 --> 01:19:11.356
lymphoblastic leukemia,

1341
01:19:12.496 --> 01:19:16.296
that were receiving 6-mercaptopurine, a different

1342
01:19:16.336 --> 01:19:20.176
thiopurine. And the question was: Are there sequence variants associated

1343
01:19:20.216 --> 01:19:24.176
with anything in the nudix family, okay, that is

1344
01:19:24.236 --> 01:19:27.856
associated with drug responses? And he found

1345
01:19:27.916 --> 01:19:30.956
an intergenic variant in an

1346
01:19:30.996 --> 01:19:34.976
enhancer that regulates the level of NUDT15 expression.

1347
01:19:34.996 --> 01:19:38.496
And what the graph shows is that patients that have one or two copies of that

1348
01:19:38.596 --> 01:19:42.156
variant have a lower 6-MP dose intensity.

1349
01:19:42.216 --> 01:19:45.676
Basically, what that means is that if you have that

1350
01:19:45.736 --> 01:19:49.556
variant, you're more likely to experience myelosuppression

1351
01:19:49.636 --> 01:19:53.556
at the same dose of 6-MP. Okay. The higher the level

1352
01:19:53.566 --> 01:19:56.996
of NUDT5 expression, the more toxic the drug is.

1353
01:19:57.056 --> 01:20:00.976
It's probably more toxic to the leukemia cells, but in this study, also

1354
01:20:01.016 --> 01:20:02.276
toxic to the normal cells.

1355
01:20:03.856 --> 01:20:05.316
Okay. So let me just

1356
01:20:06.356 --> 01:20:08.036
bring it back to metastasis for one second.

1357
01:20:08.616 --> 01:20:12.566
We know that there is this tendency to trend towards increased

1358
01:20:12.616 --> 01:20:16.296
higher mitochondrial metabolism, and we think that's important for metastasis,

1359
01:20:16.336 --> 01:20:20.296
including in people. The question that we have to address now is

1360
01:20:20.356 --> 01:20:24.176
whether that transition also involves a change in the

1361
01:20:24.196 --> 01:20:28.136
mode of purine metabolism. I think this is plausible because

1362
01:20:28.236 --> 01:20:31.636
maintaining purine pools, we think, is a metabolic

1363
01:20:31.736 --> 01:20:35.524
bottleneckThat cells have to be able to overcome

1364
01:20:36.204 --> 01:20:40.024
during metastasis, and the ability to maintain flexibility about the way these

1365
01:20:40.064 --> 01:20:42.124
two compensatory pathways are regulated

1366
01:20:43.024 --> 01:20:44.944
may give cells a way to

1367
01:20:46.284 --> 01:20:47.084
tolerate that.

1368
01:20:48.344 --> 01:20:52.284
Okay, in the last minute, I just want to back out for one more second and just say

1369
01:20:52.744 --> 01:20:53.144
something

1370
01:20:54.184 --> 01:20:57.244
else about the metabolic network. The network is there.

1371
01:20:57.304 --> 01:21:00.984
Okay, that is a poster that hangs in my office that I look at every day.

1372
01:21:02.584 --> 01:21:03.004
And

1373
01:21:03.904 --> 01:21:07.524
what's a little bit depressing about the poster is that almost every reaction

1374
01:21:08.064 --> 01:21:10.044
on there is older than me.

1375
01:21:11.104 --> 01:21:12.154
Okay? And that leads

1376
01:21:13.224 --> 01:21:16.844
to the perception that we know everything there is to know about

1377
01:21:16.904 --> 01:21:19.884
metabolism. I think that that's not true,

1378
01:21:20.704 --> 01:21:24.644
and I would bet that most of the people in here also think that that's not true.

1379
01:21:24.784 --> 01:21:28.344
And because I think there's a big gap between

1380
01:21:28.544 --> 01:21:32.104
knowing the enzymes in the pathway and knowing how they're spatially

1381
01:21:32.184 --> 01:21:35.524
organized to maximize their regulation. Okay?

1382
01:21:35.544 --> 01:21:39.514
It's a little bit like knowing all of the pieces in the Lego set, but not knowing

1383
01:21:39.544 --> 01:21:42.344
what the Lego set is supposed to look like when it's built out into three

1384
01:21:42.404 --> 01:21:45.364
dimensions. And so, I'll just

1385
01:21:46.124 --> 01:21:49.023
maybe say that I think there's a lot more to learn.

1386
01:21:49.184 --> 01:21:53.054
One aspect of that is that if you think about the pathway, you get the

1387
01:21:53.104 --> 01:21:56.264
impression that all pathways

1388
01:21:56.764 --> 01:21:59.954
operate like this with soluble substrates and

1389
01:22:00.064 --> 01:22:03.704
enzymes that have to encounter each other stochastically by

1390
01:22:03.784 --> 01:22:05.424
diffusing through an aqueous milieu.

1391
01:22:05.904 --> 01:22:09.364
When in reality, I would bet that there are a lot of pathways that actually operate

1392
01:22:09.404 --> 01:22:13.204
more like the purinosome, with transient complexes that come together and come

1393
01:22:13.224 --> 01:22:16.894
apart in order to regulate flux, because that would give you two very different

1394
01:22:17.004 --> 01:22:20.764
states of metabolic activity through a pathway, even when all the

1395
01:22:20.804 --> 01:22:22.264
enzymes are present. Okay?

1396
01:22:23.124 --> 01:22:26.464
This is an old idea that goes back to the 1970s at least,

1397
01:22:27.104 --> 01:22:30.194
but we have identified very few of these super complexes,

1398
01:22:31.004 --> 01:22:34.064
and even fewer that have any role in human

1399
01:22:34.084 --> 01:22:37.964
physiology. But I think now is a good time to go looking for them again.

1400
01:22:38.104 --> 01:22:41.724
Co-evolutionary analysis is a powerful way to infer

1401
01:22:41.784 --> 01:22:45.704
where interactions may occur, and human genetics gives us

1402
01:22:45.764 --> 01:22:49.224
insight into when missense variants in

1403
01:22:49.304 --> 01:22:52.784
protein-protein interaction domains actually cause metabolic

1404
01:22:52.824 --> 01:22:56.784
disturbance in people. Okay? So this is something that we will be working on for

1405
01:22:56.824 --> 01:23:00.724
the next few years. And let me just stop and thank the people who did all

1406
01:23:00.764 --> 01:23:01.224
the work.

1407
01:23:02.144 --> 01:23:05.894
For the purine metabolism, basically all Zheng and Fong, two great postdocs in my

1408
01:23:05.964 --> 01:23:06.244
lab.

1409
01:23:07.364 --> 01:23:07.544
And

1410
01:23:08.344 --> 01:23:12.204
I want to thank the patients and families who participated in

1411
01:23:12.224 --> 01:23:13.724
our clinical studies. Thanks very much.

1412
01:23:20.344 --> 01:23:21.204
Questions for Ralph?

1413
01:23:23.044 --> 01:23:25.544
Great talk. Omid Tajiasani from Case Western.

1414
01:23:26.164 --> 01:23:29.764
I had a question regarding the TCA cycle activity on metastatic

1415
01:23:29.774 --> 01:23:33.724
tumors. I was wondering if these tumors already have higher TCA

1416
01:23:33.764 --> 01:23:37.684
on their primary site, and then they're going to a new host organs,

1417
01:23:38.144 --> 01:23:41.964
or they exchange that or convert their metabolism when they arrive at the

1418
01:23:41.984 --> 01:23:42.604
host organs.

1419
01:23:42.944 --> 01:23:44.764
Yeah, this is a great question, and

1420
01:23:45.644 --> 01:23:46.754
I think it's the former.

1421
01:23:47.924 --> 01:23:51.784
And the reason I say that is because both in lung cancer

1422
01:23:52.464 --> 01:23:53.404
and now in

1423
01:23:54.564 --> 01:23:57.684
clear cell renal cell carcinoma, we've sort of gone back and looked

1424
01:23:57.844 --> 01:24:01.664
at the level of variable mitochondrial metabolism and then followed

1425
01:24:01.744 --> 01:24:04.564
outcomes of those patients. And in both cases,

1426
01:24:05.464 --> 01:24:09.444
the level of it, to be really precise about

1427
01:24:09.454 --> 01:24:12.864
this, it's the level of TCA cycle intermediate labeling with

1428
01:24:12.904 --> 01:24:16.604
carbon-13 during an infusion of something like carbon-13 glucose.

1429
01:24:16.664 --> 01:24:20.444
That level of labeling, basically, if you just dichotomize

1430
01:24:20.664 --> 01:24:24.224
the group into ones that are higher or lower than the median, in both

1431
01:24:24.304 --> 01:24:28.074
cases, in the primary tumor, high levels of labeling predict worse

1432
01:24:28.204 --> 01:24:31.904
outcomes. And the worse outcomes in those two diseases basically means whether or

1433
01:24:31.944 --> 01:24:33.124
not you got metastasis.

1434
01:24:33.744 --> 01:24:34.044
Thank you.

1435
01:24:34.464 --> 01:24:34.784
Thank you.

1436
01:24:36.384 --> 01:24:40.234
Hi, Ralph. This is very elegant work, and I'm very familiar with

1437
01:24:40.284 --> 01:24:44.264
the paper because I presented it in our lab's journal club several months before.

1438
01:24:44.304 --> 01:24:46.664
This is when you get a really hard question.

1439
01:24:48.224 --> 01:24:48.973
Okay, so I have-

1440
01:24:49.044 --> 01:24:52.163
Supplemental data, figure 10C, you should...

1441
01:24:54.304 --> 01:24:57.884
Yeah, because I work on how pyrimidine synthase regulates the chemo sensitivity.

1442
01:24:58.764 --> 01:25:02.744
So I have two brief questions. The first is in the GCI paper published by

1443
01:25:02.804 --> 01:25:06.504
the lab in the Sinjude. They point out

1444
01:25:06.724 --> 01:25:10.624
that in the leukemia, the NUDT15 also regulates the

1445
01:25:13.164 --> 01:25:16.684
salvage pathway activity. But in your paper, in hela cells, it has

1446
01:25:16.744 --> 01:25:19.614
nothing to do with the salvage pathway activity.

1447
01:25:19.934 --> 01:25:23.684
Is there any cell type-specific regulation of how

1448
01:25:23.744 --> 01:25:25.544
NUDT5 regulates purine synthesis?

1449
01:25:26.264 --> 01:25:29.974
Yeah, that's a great question. I think there probably is, and my guess is that

1450
01:25:30.204 --> 01:25:32.424
it comes down to the

1451
